# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The given code is an implementation of a method named canMakeArithmeticProgression, which determines whether the given array arr can be rearranged to form an arithmetic progression.

Here's how the code works:

The arr array is sorted using the Arrays.sort() method. Sorting the array is important because in an arithmetic progression, the elements are arranged in a specific order.

The variable diff is initialized as the difference between the second element (arr[1]) and the first element (arr[0]). This will be the common difference for the arithmetic progression.

The variable temp is set to true. It will be used to keep track of whether all the adjacent element differences match the common difference.

A loop iterates from the second element (i=1) to the second-to-last element (i<arr.length-1). This loop compares the difference between the current element (arr[i+1]) and the previous element (arr[i]) with the common difference (diff).

If the difference between the current and previous elements matches the common difference, the loop continues to the next iteration using the continue statement.

If the difference does not match the common difference, temp is set to false, indicating that the array cannot form an arithmetic progression.

Finally, after the loop, the value of temp is checked. If it is still true, the method returns true indicating that the array can form an arithmetic progression. Otherwise, it returns false.

In summary, the code checks if the given array can be sorted into an arithmetic progression by comparing the differences between adjacent elements. If all the differences match the common difference, it returns true; otherwise, it returns false.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach used in the given code can be summarized as follows:

Sort the array in ascending order using the Arrays.sort() method. Sorting the array helps in identifying the order of the elements in an arithmetic progression.

Calculate the common difference (diff) between the second element (arr[1]) and the first element (arr[0]).

Iterate through the array starting from the second element (i=1) up to the second-to-last element (i<arr.length-1).

For each iteration, check if the difference between the current element (arr[i+1]) and the previous element (arr[i]) is equal to the common difference (diff).

If the difference matches, continue to the next iteration.

If the difference does not match, set the temp variable to false, indicating that the array cannot form an arithmetic progression.

After the loop, check the value of the temp variable. If it is still true, return true to indicate that the array can form an arithmetic progression. Otherwise, return false.

In summary, the code checks if the given array can be rearranged to form an arithmetic progression by comparing the differences between adjacent elements. If all the differences match the common difference, the code returns true; otherwise, it returns false.

